The paper deals with a lower bound on the average probability of error for a two-user multiple-access channel, which is a topic in information theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the study of the relationship between average and maximal error probabilities, which falls under the sub-category cs.ITP (Information Theory and Probability). The use of sphere packing bounds suggests that the paper may also be relevant to cs.MM (Multimedia), which deals with data compression and transmission. The paper's focus on multiple-access channels and the study of input distributions suggests that it may also be relevant to cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
